one:OE.one:T: One-sided limit: Can be denoted as limit as x approaches from left and right, respectively
Limits at infinity: Evaluation of expression as the variable goes to positive or negative infinity
Sequence limits: Expresses the limits of values within a sequence as the we progress along the sequence (using n instead of x), can be broken down into the superior and inferior limits
G | Derivatives (Single independent variables): Same notation for both scalar- and vector-valued functions
Newton derivative notation: Uses prime ticks to denote derivatives of functions, sometimes roman numerals in parentheses replace multiple prime marks
Leibniz derivative notation: Uses d over dx to denote derivatives of functions, in which case, the derivative part of the notation can be separated and treated as a function in itself
Usually for derivatives with respect to time
G | Derivatives (multiple independent variables, scalar-valued functions):
Partial derivatives (for scalar-valued functions): derivative with respect to one variable in a function with multiple independent variables
Directional derivative: derivative with respect to a direction specified by a unit vector defined by the components that compose the function *
Gradient: vector of partial derivatives each independent variable of a function
G | Derivatives (multiple independent variables, vector-valued functions):
Vectors: n-long column of real numbers, can be denoted in various ways
Bold, overhead right harpoon, or underline tilde can all be used to denote vectors
Arrows above 0 or 1 represent vectors of all 0s and 1s, respectively
Vector-valued functions: convert scalar inputs into a vector output (i.e., maps a set of real number into a vector space composed of n real numbers), denoted by arrow above function*
Is composed of separate functions for each output component vector of the output vector
Vector norm: a function that provides some measure of distance from the origin for a vector
L1 norm: sum of absolute values of the vector, less influenced by outliers than L2

Dot inner product: dot product of two vectors
Good visualization: Cross Product and Dot Product: Visual explanation
Orthogonality: the property between two vectors that have a zero dot product

Cross product: defined only for vectors with 3 dimensions, {is always perpendicular to the plane between the two vectors with a length proportional to the area of the parallelogram formed by the two vectors*}
Matrices: rectangular array of numbers of size i (row) and j (column), often denoted by an italicized capital letter
Number of rows always given first
Matrix entries: single entries/numbers within the matrix, indicated by their row and column (in that order)
Common to omit comma separating subscripts
or are also contenvionally used to stand for a singular value of a matrix
Represents a matrix of all 1s with the shape m x n
Matrix multiplication: multiplication between two matrices where the number of columns of the first matrix is equal to the number of rows in the second matrix

one:OE.one:T: Each individual entry can be characterized by:
Identity matrix: square matrix whose diagonal entries are all 0 and main diagonal entries are all 1, denoted by the italicized capital letter I
In terms of linear transformations, transformation by an identity matrix does nothing*
Inverse matrix: a matrix that, when multiplied with its original matrix, results in an identity matrix
In terms of linear transformations, the inverse matrix is the matrix that does the reverse linear transformation of the original matrix*
Transposed matrix: a matrix derived from another matrix by swapping rows and columns
Matrix null space/Matrix kernel: the set of all n-dimensional column vectors witin the matrix's column space such that
In terms of linear transformations, is the set of vectors that get compressed onto the origin after transformation by the matrix*
This is because regardless of linear transformation, the origin will always stay constant
Basically the solution space of a matrix systems of equation

Matrix rank: dimension of the vector space spanned by its column, corresponds to its maximal number of linearly independent columns (i.e., how many columns aren't a linear combination of those before it)*
In terms of linear transformation, is the number of dimensions in the output if the matrix were to be treated as a matrix*
Intuitive way of explaining is "how many unique ingredients make up this matrix?", useful for compression
Determinant: the factor by which the linear transformation represented by a matrix changes any area/volume/higher dimensional object, is only applicable to square matrices*
